      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4db33639637579a7",
      "text": "While [U.C. Berkeley was established in 1868](https://oac.cdlib.org/view?docId=hb4v19n9zb;NAAN=13030&doc.view=frames&chunk.id=div00277&toc.depth=1&toc.id=div00277&brand=oac4), it wasn't until 1923 that Pepper had a hand in establishing a full arts program.\n\n> In 1869 freehand drawing was required for students in the agriculture curriculum, but, until 1923, a designated art department didn’t exist. It took the insight and persistence of two professors, Worth Ryder and Stephen Pepper, to establish a curriculum that balanced studio practice, theory and criticism, and art history, thereby securing the place of art at Berkeley. \n\n* Source:  [\"The Flowering of Arts and Humanities\" | Builders of Berkeley | 2021](https://web.archive.org/web/20201028203753/https://builders.berkeley.edu/stories/flowering-arts-and-humanities/)"
    },
